For both reactions the Diels–Alder reaction forms the corresponding cyclohexene‐ or bicyclic product.

1. **(E)-penta‑1,3‑diene + acrylonitrile** (thermal Diels–Alder)

   \[
   \text{CH}_2=\text{CH–CH}=\text{CH–CH}_3
   +\,\text{CH}_2=\text{CH–CN}
   \;\longrightarrow\;
   \color{blue}{5\text{-methylcyclohex-3-ene-1-carbonitrile}}
   \]

   The new ring contains a double bond between the third and fourth carbons (hence “‑3‑ene”), the nitrile group at position 1, and a methyl group at position 5.

2. **Cyclopentadiene + methyl acrylate** (thermal Diels–Alder)

   \[
   \text{cyclopentadiene}
   +\,\text{CH}_2=\text{CH–COOCH}_3
   \;\longrightarrow\;
   \color{blue}{\text{methyl}\,(1R,2R,4R)\text{-bicyclo[2.2.1]hept-5-ene-2-carboxylate}}
   \]

   This is the *endo* adduct. The ester group is situated on the same side as the larger bridge, giving the absolute configuration (1R,2R,4R) at the three stereogenic centers.

Therefore, the correct pair of product descriptions is given by choice:

**C** – A = 5‑methylcyclohex‑3‑ene‑1‑carbonitrile;  
  B = methyl (1R,2R,4R)‑bicyclo[2.2.1]hept‑5‑ene‑2‑carboxylate.

