Let  

* \(R_0=5\) – radius of the largest disk,
* \(R_k=\bigl(\tfrac23\bigr)^{\,k}R_0\) – radius of the \(k\)-th disk ( \(k=0,1,2,\dots \) ),
* \(\omega=\dfrac{\pi}{6}\;\text{rad/s}\) – the rate at which each disk spins **relative** to the disk to which it is attached.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  Position of Alice

Write the position of Alice as a complex number.
The vector from the centre of disk \(k\) to the centre of disk \(k+1\) has length \(R_k\) and turns with the orientation of disk \(k\); that orientation is \((k+1)\omega t\).

\[
z(t)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} R_k e^{\,i (k+1)\omega t}
    \;=\;R_0\,e^{i\omega t}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\bigl(\tfrac23\,e^{i\omega t}\bigr)^k
\]

The geometric series gives  

\[
\boxed{\,z(t)= R_0\;\frac{e^{\,i\omega t}}
              {1-\frac23e^{\,i\omega t}}\, } \qquad (1)
\]

At \(t=0\) all arms are colinear on the \(x\)-axis, so \(z(0)=15\) (the total radius of the “arm armour”).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  Speed

Differentiate (1):

\[
\begin{aligned}
z'(t)
  &= R_0\,\frac{i\omega e^{i\omega t}}
              {\bigl(1-\tfrac23e^{i\omega t}\bigr)^2 }  \\[2mm]
  &= i\omega R_0 e^{i\omega t}
        \bigl(1-\tfrac23e^{i\omega t}\bigr)^{-2}
\end{aligned}
\]

The modulus of a complex number \(u\) is \(|u|\).  Using  
\(|e^{i\omega t}|=1\)

\[
|z'(t)|
   = \frac{\omega R_0}
          {\bigl|1-\tfrac23e^{i\omega t}\bigr|^{\,2}}
   =\frac{\omega R_0}
         {\,1+\bigl(\tfrac23\bigr)^2-2\cdot\tfrac23\cos(\omega t)}.
\]

Insert the known constants:

\[
|z'(t)|
 = \frac{\displaystyle \bigl(\frac{\pi}{6}\bigr)\,5}
        {\displaystyle\frac{13}{9}-\frac{4}{3}\cos(\omega t)}
 =\frac{15\pi/2}{\,13-12\cos(\omega t)} .\tag{2}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  Arc length after 12 s

The length travelled from \(t=0\) to \(t=12\) is

\[
L=\int_0^{12}\! |z'(t)|\,dt
   =\frac{15\pi}{2}
     \int_0^{12}\frac{dt}{\,13-12\cos(\omega t)} .
\]

Set \(u=\omega t\) (so \(dt=\frac{du}{\omega}\) and \(u\) goes from \(0\) to \(2\pi\) because \(\omega=\pi/6\)):

\[
L = \frac{15\pi}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{\omega}
    \int_0^{2\pi}\frac{du}{\,13-12\cos u}
  = \frac{15\pi}{2}\cdot\frac{6}{\pi}
    \int_0^{2\pi}\frac{du}{\,13-12\cos u}
  = 45\;\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{du}{\,13-12\cos u}. \tag{3}
\]

The standard integral (for \(a>b>0\))

\[
\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{du}{a-b\cos u}
    =\frac{2\pi}{\sqrt{a^2-b^2}}
\]

gives, with \(a=13,\; b=12\),

\[
\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{du}{\,13-12\cos u}
      =\frac{2\pi}{\sqrt{13^2-12^2}}
      =\frac{2\pi}{5}. 
\]

Insert this into (3):

\[
L = 45 \cdot \frac{2\pi}{5}
   = 18\pi .
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
\[
\boxed{\,L = 18\pi \text{ units}\,}
\]

