Using the usual detailed–balance treatment of a solar cell, the incoming photon flux from the Sun (treated as a black‑body at temperature \(T_s\) and radius \(R_{\odot}\)) is  

\[
\Phi_{\rm in}
   =\frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{\,2}}{d_{\odot}^{\,2}}\;
     \int_{\nu_{g}}^{\infty}
     \frac{2\nu^{2}}{c^{2}}\;
     \frac{1}{\exp\!\left(\dfrac{h\nu}{k_{B}T_{s}}\right)-1}\;
     d\nu ,
\]

where \(\nu_g=E_g/h\).  
When a photon has energy \(h\nu\ge E_g\) the cell can convert an electron–hole pair into a useful electrical energy
\(E_g=h\nu_g\).  Assuming \(100\%\) absorption (i.e. every photon above the band‑gap creates one electron–hole pair that is extracted as work), the power delivered by a cell of area \(A\) is

\[
P_{\text{out}}
   =A\,E_g\,\Phi_{\rm in}
   =A\,x_g k_{B}T_{s}\,
            \frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{\,2}}{d_{\odot}^{\,2}}\;
            \frac{2}{c^{2}}
            \int_{\nu_{g}}^{\infty}
            \frac{\nu^{2}}{e^{h\nu/k_{B}T_{s}}-1}\;d\nu .
\]

Changing the integration variable to the dimensionless quantity  

\[
u=\frac{h\nu}{k_{B}T_{s}}\qquad (\; \nu=\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\,u,\;\; d\nu=\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\,du\;),
\]

and recalling \(x_g=u_{\rm g}\), gives  

\[
\Phi_{\rm in}
      =\frac{\pi R_{\odot}^{\,2}}{d_{\odot}^{\,2}}\;
        \frac{2}{c^{2}}
        \Big(\frac{k_{B}T_{s}}{h}\Big)^{3}
        \int_{x_g}^{\infty}\frac{u^{2}}{e^{u}-1}\;du .
\]

Hence

\[
\boxed{\,%
P_{\text{out}}
   =\frac{2\pi\,A\,R_{\odot}^{\,2}}{d_{\odot}^{\,2}}\;
     \frac{x_g\,(k_{B}T_{s})^{4}}{c^{2}\,h^{3}}\;
     \int_{x_g}^{\infty}\frac{u^{2}}{e^{\,u}-1}\;du\; }
\]

or, equivalently (since the integral can be expressed in terms of polylogarithms),

\[
P_{\text{out}}
   =\frac{2\pi\,A\,R_{\odot}^{\,2}}{d_{\odot}^{\,2}}\;
     \frac{x_g\,(k_{B}T_{s})^{4}}{c^{2}\,h^{3}}\;
     \Big[\,2\,\operatorname{Li}_{3}\big(e^{-x_g}\big)
           +2x_g\,\operatorname{Li}_{2}\big(e^{-x_g}\big)
           +x_g^{2}\,\operatorname{Li}_{1}\big(e^{-x_g}\big)\Big].
\]

All quantities in the expression are defined in the problem statement:  
\(x_g=h\nu_g/(k_{B}T_{s})=E_g/(k_{B}T_{s})\), \(A\) = cell area, \(R_{\odot}\) = Sun radius, \(d_{\odot}\) = Earth–Sun distance, \(T_s\) = Sun’s surface temperature, and \(c,\;h,\;k_{B}\) are the speed of light, Planck’s constant and Boltzmann’s constant, respectively.

